module lexer
  source: ["lexer.ly"]
  why: "Tokenizer for Lyric source. Produces a Token stream classified by the TokenKind enum. The Lexer is a stateful scanner tracking line/column/position so every Token carries an accurate Span for downstream error reporting and source mapping."

  doc "Architecture":
    """
    Linear scan: raw text → Token stream. The Lexer walks the source
    byte-by-byte producing Token values with kind, text, and span.

    Keyword recognition uses a Dict<Sym, TokenKind> built once at
    construction and consulted by scan_ident. Hard keywords (class, func,
    struct, …) lex to their specific TokenKind. Contextual keywords (doc,
    why, source, field, lock, implements, embed) are emitted as LIdent and
    resolved by the parser based on position.

    LexerState (save_state / restore_state) snapshots pos/line/column,
    bracket_depth, and any peeked token, enabling parser backtracking for
    ambiguous constructs such as struct literals vs blocks. The snapshot
    is a simple value copy — cheap and side-effect free.

    Bracket tracking: bracket_depth counts open () and [] only. Newlines
    inside brackets are suppressed (no SNewline emitted) so that
    multi-line argument lists / list literals don't terminate statements.
    Braces {} delimit blocks and do NOT participate in bracket_depth.

    String forms: scan_string, scan_triple_string, scan_fstring, and
    scan_char_lit handle the four literal shapes. F-strings encode escaped
    braces {{ and }} as sentinel bytes \\x01 and \\x02 in the token text
    so the parser can later distinguish them from interpolation
    boundaries; the parser is responsible for decoding the sentinels.

    Comments are NOT emitted as tokens. The scan loop consumes // and
    /* */ comments and discards them, keeping the token stream clean
    for parsing.

    Token splitting (e.g. >> → > >) for nested generics like Dict<Dict<V>>
    is explicitly NOT a lexer responsibility — the lexer emits OShr and
    the parser uses pushBack to split it when a closing > is expected.
    """

  invariant "Keyword Lookup":
    procedural
    """
    Keyword resolution MUST go through lookup_keyword, which consults
    the Lexer's keywords Dict<Sym, TokenKind> built once by
    init_keywords. Lookup is O(1) via Sym hashing.

    Hard keywords (KLyric, KFunc, KClass, KStruct, KEnum, KInterface,
    KImpl, KLet, KIf, KElse, KFor, KWhile, KMatch, KReturn, KBreak,
    KContinue, KTrue, KFalse, KNil, KSelf, KMut, …) always lex to
    their specific TokenKind.

    Contextual keywords — doc, why, source, fake, field, lock,
    implements, embed — are emitted as LIdent. The parser resolves
    them positionally so they remain usable as ordinary identifiers
    in field/param/variable names.
    """

  invariant "No Line Continuation":
    procedural
    """
    The lexer does NOT support line continuation across binary
    operators. A multi-condition expression MUST live on a single
    logical line or be extracted into a helper.

    bracket_depth tracks () and [] nesting only. While bracket_depth
    > 0, newline bytes are consumed without emitting SNewline so that
    multi-line argument lists and list literals stay one statement.
    {} braces delimit blocks and MUST NOT increment bracket_depth.

    bracket_depth is part of LexerState and MUST be saved/restored
    by save_state and restore_state so backtracking does not corrupt
    newline suppression.
    """

  invariant "F-String Sentinels":
    procedural
    """
    Inside an f-string, escaped braces {{ and }} MUST be stored in
    the token text as sentinel bytes \\x01 and \\x02 respectively.
    Real { and } in the token text continue to mark interpolation
    boundaries.

    The parser is responsible for decoding \\x01 → { and \\x02 → }
    when materializing the literal string segments of the f-string.
    The lexer MUST NOT emit { or } for escaped braces — that would
    be indistinguishable from interpolation.
    """

  invariant "Comment Handling":
    procedural
    """
    Comments are NOT emitted as tokens. The scan loop consumes //
    line comments and /* */ block comments and discards them.
    Downstream consumers (parser, formatter) MUST NOT expect comment
    tokens in the stream.

    Tooling that needs comments preserved must extend the lexer to
    collect them into a side channel; the bootstrap pipeline does
    not require this.
    """

  invariant "Token Splitting Boundary":
    procedural
    """
    Nested generics like Dict<Dict<V>> produce the source text >>,
    which the lexer MUST emit as a single OShr token. The lexer does
    NOT attempt to split OShr into two PGt tokens based on context.

    Splitting OShr → PGt PGt for closing nested generic argument
    lists is a parser-side responsibility, handled via a pushBack
    mechanism in the parser's expectation logic.
    """


  typedef TokenKind: enum { KLyric, KFunc, KClass, KStruct, KEnum, KInterface, KRelation, KField, KDestructor, KEmbed, KImport, KImplements, KImpl, KAs, KIs, KType, KWhere, KOwns, KRefs, KMut, KSelf, KFrom, KTrue, KFalse, KNil, KPub, KLet, KIf, KElse, KFor, KIn, KWhile, KMatch, KReturn, KBreak, KContinue, KSpawn, KSelect, KCase, KLock, KYield, LIdent, LIntLit, LFloatLit, LStringLit, LTripleString, LFString, LCharLit, LBacktickSym, PLParen, PRParen, PLBrace, PRBrace, PLBracket, PRBracket, PComma, PColon, PDot, PArrow, PFatArrow, PBiArrow, PPipe, PQuestion, PLt, PGt, OAssign, OPlus, OMinus, OStar, OSlash, OPercent, OEqEq, OBangEq, OLtEq, OGtEq, OAmpAmp, OPipePipe, OBang, OAmp, OCaret, OShl, OShr, OPlusEq, OMinusEq, OStarEq, OSlashEq, SNewline, SEOF }
    source: lexer.ly:15

